es.  Plus, the amount of hitpoint and balanced resist-gear available significantly decreases a caster's potential in pvp- it is practically impossible for a caster to 'resist' a hefty 2-handed hit or a backstab.  Wizards are possibly worst-off in all this.  Clerics and druids have the opportunity to outheal nukes efficiently, and with a damage-shield plus healing, they can make even a well-geared melee think a bit before they attack.  Mages and necros both have pets, and a good array of spells to back them up, chanters have mezzes and debuffs.  A wizard's only chance of killing a well-geared melee is to nuke quickly, position well and hope for the best on the resists.  <br><br>I do however think, that the way to go about changing the way manaburn works is important to ensure that ganking with a death-touch then gating to a non-pvp area doesn't happen that often.  I concede Auro's point- there aren't that many manaburn wizards now who do use it as a death-touch ganking tool, but this needs to be changed for the future, not the present.  A death-touch of any kind, be it dire charm or manaburn trivializes the experience of pvp...reducing it to clicking a hotkey, then the gate spell, then /afk or /camp until refresh.  <br><br>Just to pre-empt a commonly used argument by several wizards I have spoken to- they all point to Harmtouch and cry foul when people discuss nerfing manaburn.  Well, a couple of points - discipline harm-touch while very powerful, isn't a death-touch.  Secondly, due to an SK's inability to gate, you don't see many (or any in my experience) portal-camping.  Last and most importantly, it requires a fair slice of skill and ability for a shadow-knight to do the required damage putting their victim within range of HT (in an outdoor zone) against a caster who is running around and making use of the terrain &amp; levitation.  The fact that a manaburn wizard can simply hit a hotkey within spell-casting range, /loot, mod-rod and gate to a non-pvp zone makes a lot of people frustrated, understandably so.  So yes, harmtouch is instacast, yes it is powerful, but it doesn't give SKs a death-touch, especially given the skill ceiling required to hit a circle-strafing caster with 200+ ping.  Manaburn requires almost no skill to use, it's a one-click kill most of the time.<br><br>How to fix it then?  Well, my suggestion is to give it the chance of taking off between 70 and 90 percent of a player's TOTAL hps, assuming the wizard starts from full mana.  Lesser percentages if you start from less than full mana.  The wizard's total mana pool determines the exact percentage.  This balances manaburn versus all classes nicely imho.  Remove the possibility of critical blasts in mana burn in pvp ONLY.  This still allows the wizard a chance to save a raid with a crit manaburn for stupid amounts of damage, but doesn't allow them to deprive their pvp opponent of any chance whatsoever.  For all those who might say that this emasculates a wizard's ability to kill an opponent, I agree with Biguss.  A wizard who uses the right nukes, and balances damage potential with his/her mana can kill just fine without manaburn.  Especially if they have an OOR bard muling them speedsong (/hugs Voltaic).  Bear in mind that you can still lure + sunstrike + manaburn and score a kill.  And let's not forget the abuses easily introduced if you add a mod rod/MR2 and a conflag wand or two to the mix.  <br><br>For such a powerful ability there should also be hefty penalties (both PvE and PvP imho).  Current restrictions of going oom and refresh time should be kept, but here are some examples of what could be done to add an element of risk to using manaburn (there is very little now).  After casting manaburn the caster should be *stunned* for 7-10 seconds.  This is to prevent he/she from mod-rod'ing and gating to bazaar or drinking an instagate potion right after casting what still amounts to a virtual death-touch.  It also hands the advantage clearly to the player fighting the wizard.  EQ is about risk versus reward...if the wizard wants to take the risk of being stunned for up to 10 seconds within casting range of a melee with a mean 2H, or giving a caster time to pet up/waste them, chances are the wizard will think twice about using manaburn as their *only* weapon.  Not only that, but it could be easily and gently introduced in PR terms, Verant simply stating that 'the vast release of magical energies has serious short-term consequences to one who uses it, etc, etc.&quot;  This change would also makes the manaburn ability more of a last resort, which is how it was intended PvE, and what these changes would try to achieve pvp-wise.  This still makes the wizard a fearsome pvp class solo...with another manaburn wizard added in however, you would just have to throw up your hands and eat the death.  Still, it would be a step in the right direction imho- sticking with current 'limitations' is a road to disaster and frustration for those ganked by its raw power.  <br><br>Just my 2cp.<br><br> <p>Taranna Dhossarim57 Cleric, Seekers of Divinity</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/usomthor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>somthor</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#333333>(3/14/02 12:04:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub83.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=625.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.iofthestorm.org/images/EQicon.bmp WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Regardng Dire charm</span><hr size=1> let them keep the skill but then give Melees a inate resistance such that it about negates it<br><br>so as a 60th warrior getting manaburned would reduce my curent 